Introduction

We were provided a sample of 21,613 observations with 14 variables. We wanted to see what drives the prices of houses through the variables given to us.The continuous variables that we had we: sqft_living,sqft_lot,bathrooms,bedrooms,yr_built. The categorical variables were: waterfront,view,condition,yr_renovated,zip_code,floors,grade. It is important to analyze these variables thoroughly so that we can answer When,What and Why some of these variable if not all drive the prices for houses.

We found that the median price was the best indicator since the price was skewed.Moreover through correlation test, we found out that there is a strong positive correlation between sqft_living and price. However, because of random nature of sft_lot, it did not give us much useful information.Below we have a clear presentation of median price with sqft_living.

Finding Number 1

We started our investigation with when from our 3 Ws(when,what,why). When did the price vary throughout the years and if there is a something unusual in the pattern. Our findings is below:

We see that there is a drop in median prices of houses built around 1945, which could be the quality of the houses. Also, we can see that the before 1950s, it is more expensive to sell a built house built before 1950s than to buy a renovated house of year built before 1950s..Furthermore, we can see that even after the rise of median prices of houses built, the median price does not go beyond $600,000 until very recently. Whilst, buying a renovated house cost well above $600,000 after 1980s.

What variables could be driving the median prices throughout? From our correlation coefficient, we see a positive relation with bathrooms,floors and grade. This will lead us to our next finding.

Finding Number 2

After analyzing the median prices throughout the years, we decided to what variables could be cause behind. Grade and condition were chosen first because positive correlation with price.

Most of the condition 1 and condition 2 houses were built in the 1900 and 1925 respectively. The median price of condition 2 was also very high above $2000,000 . This is consistent with the high median price for built houses before 1950s. At the same time, we can see that condition 3 and 4 are built in 2000s where condition 4 is consistent with the rising house prices in the 2000s in finding 1. Grade also gives us the information that most houses built in the 1900s have a grade higher than 7. But most of the houses built in 2000 make up higher proportion of the higher grades which rises the median prices.

This leads us to our last finding, which of the two, condition or grade is better at telling the story? and why?

Finding Number 3

The pattern is consistent throughout all the conditions with same intercept and gradient.

Pattern is not consistent throughout all the grades.This means that condition is more reliable predictor that depicts the up and downs of median prices throughout the years.

Conclusion

The summary to take away is price has strong positive correlation with sqft_living condition is a good predictor of price and older houses had higher grades,higher median prices,but have low condition scores.This was just a slice of the analysis that determines the prices for houses in the market.
